author: @rs646dd
text:
This film is a monster movie, but it is also an anti-war film.
It is estimated that of the 2 million Japanese servicemen who died in World War II, about half died of starvation or disease, and about 100,000 civilians were burned to death in one night during the Tokyo Air Raid of March 10, 1945; many lives were lost. And now, in Gaza and Ukraine, many are dying.
In fact, Godzilla is not the main character in this film. The main characters are the soldiers who returned home alive but with deep emotional scars, and the citizens who survived the horrific air raids.

author: @Caries9
text:
"In a movie, there is a line, 'Someone's got to do it,' but in Japanese, it's actually, 'Someone's got to draw the short straw.' The phrase 'drawing the short straw' （貧乏くじを引く: Draw a poor lottery)comes from a Japanese proverb, indicating being involved in difficulties or unfortunate situations. Specifically, it expresses encountering bad situations or events and facing undesirable outcomes or impacts. This is often used to describe situations where one feels unlucky.

In essence, 'Someone's got to do it' and 'Someone's got to draw the short straw' have slightly different nuances:

1. 'Someone's got to do it' implies a strong demand or pressure that everyone should fulfill some responsibility or task in a given situation.

2. On the other hand, 'Someone's got to draw the short straw' suggests a sense that someone needs to experience and confront fate or difficulties. It has a somewhat fatalistic tone, pointing to situations where one must deal with unavoidable hardships or challenges.

In short, the former emphasizes a broad sense of responsibility or task-sharing, while the latter sees fate or difficulties as something that individuals must personally face. The phrase captures the idea of Godzilla, who cannot be satisfied or defeated by a sense of duty alone, and those who deliberately choose to confront him.

movies.

Shin Godzilla (2016)

author: @Gabriel-G.
text:
Honestly, what's the hype with this one?
Yeah, okay, classic Godzilla is back. Let's just forget Shin Godzilla is a thing.
We KNOW what's going to happen. "Unknown creature" is Godzilla, who's destroying absolutely everything and is a threat to humanity. Government fights the creature with military equipment and fails. Then they do some research on Godzilla and find its origin, biology-- allat. Then, using this knowledge, they fight Godzilla again and eventually win.
Sure, many things can happen in between that copy-paste structure, but unless they bring in something new to the plot's structure or to Godzilla (like Shin Godzilla, introducing the concept of Godzilla evolving based on the dangers against it), what is there to get excited about aside from the same thing you've already seen in previous films?
Yes, it's cool that Godzilla is a bad guy, given how much he's been depicted as a "hero", both in recent and archaic media. However, you can only do so much with Godzilla being a villian, that being, in a nutshell, the destruction Godzilla causes and humanity's desperate attempts to stop it.
So, I'll ask again: _What's so exciting?_

Guess we'll wait and see what the next Japanese reboot's gonna be...

author: @caninekingpin7442
text: The good graphic destructive action in these movies began with RODAN'S ENTRANCE in the Legendary movie "Godzilla: King of the Monsters". Only they didn't ride his character properly for the entire movie. After his entrance he was, like, wimped down in one scene after after another until, by the end of the movie, he was portrayed as a TOTAL wimp (I don't like the alpha monster concept, Godzilla's invulnerability being OVER-done, breathing fire to heaven, sending fire out of holes in his body, exploding physically as a nuclear bomb and so forth. Maybe it's just me imagining things, but I thought I saw baby Kong emerge out of a sea of fire in the Skull Island movie). Anyway, according to the way I like these movies done, this would be about the one main sore spot I find about the last 2 Godzilla flicks. Without this particular sore spot of mine, I, personally, being a 60-year-old authority in the knowledge of these movies, would have enjoyed both somewhat more than I did. They were good. But, of course, a serious fan given these new possibilities that modern technology make possible, will chip in with something to say here. It's called advantageous greed.

author: @jingusjongus9377
text: I remember going to an artsy theater like 2 hours from where I lived when I was 16 and shin godzilla had come out semi-recently. it was the only place they were playing it and I didn't want to stream it because it was the first new toho godzilla movie that I was old enough to attend a theater to watch. Final wars came out when I was like 4 or something and while I adore the legendary ones, they just don't have the same vibe to them as the Toho ones because they're made by a totally different culture with a totally different context. My aunt took me, and when we got out she said something like "That was good, but it kind of felt more like a political drama than a godzilla movie" and I was just like... yeah, that's kinda the point lmao. While godzilla as a hero is obviously fun, it's pretty easy to see that He does his best work as a villain. He was quite literally born for the role of an extinction event with legs and a bad attitude, and it's so cool that this seems to be going in that direction.

author: @jamaal7
text: This has all the trappings of being a monumentally great film. I don't think the audiences will be sitting on their hands in between the VFX scenes. Given the accomplishments and artistry of the filmmaker, I anticipate  a thoroughly engrossing, cathartic and emotionally resonating movie, with jaw-dropping visual effects. Being a period piece, set after a catastrophic war defeat suffered by Japan, one which culminated in the atomic bombing of two of its cities, I expect a rich narrative. The tagline, "Survive and Fight" wasn't used in the trailer for nothing. I think we're going to see some heroism and courageous determination that will compel the audience to cheer for the human characters.

author: @tedkurokawa4161
text:
In the 1970s, more than 20 years after the end of World War II, a Japanese soldier who suddenly returned to Japan from the jungles of the South Pacific said, ``I am ashamed to return home.'' Ta. After the war, in the 1940s, there was a sense of shame in going to the battlefield prepared to die and then returning to your homeland alive.
The scene in which a woman pushes away a man who appears to have returned from the battlefield by saying, "You shameless one!" reminds us of the trend in Japanese society that is said to have existed in the sad past.

author: @jeremiahpheasant466
text:
For people saying this is godzilla if serazawa didn't create the oxygen destroyer, well just so you know that idea isn't new and has been done in the last Japanese films, it happened in Godzilla vs megaguirus, it even states godzilla after burning Tokyo down he left in 1954 and didn't resurface for 20 or 30 years later and then he attacked a power plant

Also godzilla final wars godzilla is also the 1954 godzilla and so is the godzilla from godzilla, Mothra, king ghidorah: giant monsters all out attack

While the rest of the godzilla's after are the second godzilla that showed up after the original died in 1954

Godzilla 1984 is the second godzilla, godzilla 1999 is the second godzilla, godzilla from godzilla against mechagodzilla and Tokyo s.o.s is also the second godzilla in their respective continuities

author: @christianarmstrong2022
text:
finally. hopefully they do a very big Godzilla project, spanning preferably dozens of movies, hitting many genres, having continuing storylines.

do Godzilla like you guys did back in the day. but a lot more… hmmm. I’m not saying every movie is about the same plot. but the overall series should have a plot point.

I think the plot point should be “do humans deserve their power”. but that really needs to be held in the hands of someone who understands how to use the symbol of Godzilla in a way that isn’t inherently fascist. I’m beginning to wonder if the brotherhood of humanity gives a fuck about anything more than profits.

shin Godzilla was lit. but it still had this tone of “what humans are doing is okay”. there was a lot of dialogue regarding how the flow of government needed to change, but it didn’t focus enough on human suffering at the hands of incapable fools. godzilla felt more like a scapegoat for the government rather than a divine intervention.

just saying. godzilla is the protector of earth, how it incarnates each film should be a representation of godzillas relationship with humanity, and humanities relationship with earth.

author: @sydneyhurst1240
text:
I love the dichotomy between toho Godzilla and Legendary Godzilla in how they are both pictured as forces of nature... makes me all the more excited for this movie. 
Legendary Godzilla is a hurricane, he doesnt care about humanity unless humanity is directly involving themselves in his business. Hes just there to do his job and defend his home
Toho Godzilla is like a man-made disaster, what happens when you poke at earth too much and earth pokes back. Hes directly targeting humans in retaliation. 

Its two very different tones for the exact same character and we get to see both at the same time via different studios (given Monarch: Legacy of monsters will be releasing a month before this)

text:
Yang paling berkuasa mengatur seluruh dunia  &  akhirat adalah Pencipta Dunia.
(semua manusia di seluruh dunia diciptakan oleh Pencipta yang sama.   Tapi di dunia ada banyak      agama      &   aliran kepercayaan serta ada juga yang atheis.      Siapakah Pencipta manusia    &   dunia ?   Banyak orang mengakui bahwa Pencipta Dunia  itu antara lain    :    Maha  Kuasa ,  Maha  Kasih.    Maka Pencipta Dunia memberitahu siapa diriNya,  pasti dengan cara yang sangat / paling mudah.    Supaya manusia bisa dengan sangat mudah juga mengetahui Pencipta manusia).
       Pemilik  Dunia  =  Pemilik  Akhirat
   Pengatur  Dunia  =  Pengatur  Akhirat

( kalau pemilik rumah,  paling berkuasa  mengatur  +  buat  peraturan  untuk orang - orang yang menghuni / mengontrak rumahnya )

author: @maxalberts2003
text: I cannot wait to see this film. Even the Japanese one that "added in" Raymond Burr was wonderful. For some reason known only to my local TV channel, the Burr version was shown annually at midnight every New Year's Eve. My parents forbid me to watch it. My grandparents simply overrode my parents' decision and watching "Godzilla" became a decade-long New Year's Eve tradition with my grandparents and me at my grandparents' house. My parents were furious but what could they do? Good times. THAT is how grandparents everywhere should be! Oh, how I miss them! And I'm seventy years old.

author: @JozettaStych
text: It's hard to be 100% certain at this point, but this looks to be a straight remake of the 1954 original.  It's postwar Japan in the early '50s, you see the destruction of the tram, there looks to be a flash or two of Odo island and both the Masaji and Shinkichi characters, a two shot of what looks like Ogata and Dr. Yamane on the battleship (presumably when the Oxygen Destroyer is deployed) and it seems fairly obvious that the woman in the window towards the beginning is Emiko.  You even see the partially-destroyed Wako building with its still-intact Hattori clock tower, and a flash of what looks a lot like the radio reporters on the observation deck of the doomed Tokyo Tower as it plummets earthward during Godzilla's second attack.  That would make this a momentous and even epochal production.  While several films have retold the original Godzilla story with varying degrees of fidelity (Godzillas '98 & '19, Shin Godzilla) a direct adaptation of Godzilla '54 has never been attempted.  It's been the lifelong impossible dream of many a hardcore Godzilla fan, to say the least.  I try not to get my hopes up about stuff, but if this is what it looks like, it's going to be off-the-Richter-scale awesome.

author: @GeekedOutNeckbeard
text:
I have REAL high hopes for THIS Godzilla movie in particular. Most of the recent movies, Shin included imo, don't really handle the human side properly anymore. It's mostly boredom and running around talking in circles getting kinda nowhere and is pointlessly dragged on to fit w/e runtime they had to appease. THIS movie has it about Godzilla, where we get to SEE Godzilla fully and his destruction all the while jumping between ACTUAL human characters for fucksakes. FINALLY. 

Doesn't seem to go with the new Godzilla trend of showing him for 3seconds then skipping to a random batch of shitty humans that circle jerk politics and then back to him for a few more and then back to boring humans. or the route that the American Monster-Verse Godzilla trend was, show Godzilla appear, then skip EVERY FUCKING FIGHT until the final one, barely show that final fight and just watch Kick-ass survive insane disasters like a Nuke... somehow. Or watch Eleven run through a city while Godzilla battles Ghidora. Yes, I'd love to watch Godzillas ass react to a strike from Ghidora while Eleven runs into a busted building and hides in a fuckin bathtub and 100% I'd love for it to be in slow-mo so I can really capture the feeling of her fear while a dope ass fight was promised to me only to be cucked in the end.

I have a feeling this one is going to be like the OG Godzilla '54. Have all the humans discovering the aftermath of the Atomic bomb, only to find out that a MASSIVE monster is awoken, then we;ll see a good chunk of Godzilla tearing shit up, while he does we'll see humans trying to sruvive his rampage, and we'll actually fucking CARE, then we'll get back to the main man and before we get too bored with his rampage, go to some humans trying to figure out how to handle him. I hope they'll give Godzilla a good amount of screentime. Rather than 5-10 minutes in a 2hr 30mins long runtime of a movie.

山崎監督作品との出会いは「三丁目の夕日」。VFXやCGでつくられた昭和の世界に何よりも惹かれました。

author: @theusher2893
text:
It's easy to forget the very first movie was a horror/monster movie that was meant as a serious analogy about the woes and uncertainty of postwar Japan.  It came out only ten years after the end of the war, when Japan was still struggling to get on its feet.  One side character even remarks "I survived Nagasaki only to get into this..."

It was only later when it became a campy joke for children.  But at first, Gojira was deadly serious.

author: @roiscavel3923
text:
It's fascinating how, after almost 70 years of various movies and depictions of Gojira on the silver screen, the japanese audiences have a dynamic, ever changing interpretation of the character and what it means. 
And yet, most of the western audiences keep trying to put it inside a tiny box: "a hero", "a villain", "good", "evil". Or worse, just a "giant monster" movie.
I'm really excited to see how this one plays out and takes a new shape, a new meaning for hopefully a new, open audience.

author: @bigmuscleguy9694
text:
So, a popular misconception going around about this trailer is that Godzilla will bite the train first, and then throw it into another train, the one with the two guys screaming. However, if you stop at around 0:13 you see that the "train" looks to have a white upper half with a teal bottom half. The train we actually see Godzilla bite is black.

This strikes me as an intentional move by director Yamazaki to build up suspense and dread by having Godzilla throw a bus, stop the train, have Godzilla notice the train, and have the lead actress notice Godzilla, and finally have Godzilla bite down on the train, most likey with the lead actress escaped because we see her running with the bandaged guy.

author: @sevenheavenhavenartandanimate
text: Godzilla feels like a force of nature that is both the consequences of the atomic bomb and also the natural disasters that always hits Japan like earthquakes and tsunamis. It's well known that Godzilla represented the fears that many Japanese held about the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki and the possibility of recurrence. As the series progressed, so did Godzilla, changing into a less destructive and more heroic character. Now, this movie seems to be going back to his destructive roots as the wrath of nature since uranium and plutonium the main ingredients for nuclear bombs are both found in nature only to be transformed into a weapon by humans as shown in the Oppenheimer movie.

author: @RoseDillinger90
text: I love that they kept the original '54 roar. That one in particular had a profound effect that meshed so well with the original movie. The other roars from King Kong vs Godzilla onward sort of deceased his fear factor despite of it being so iconic. And that was the first roar I heard! When I heard him roar for the first time in the 1954 classic, I was really taken a back because it wasn't the roar that I was used to. That one was much darker and terrifying than what I heard previously as a kid. The fact that they only used it when it called for it was a great effect, and it didn't overstay it's welcome. The terror and bone-chilling feeling of that roar combined with the actions of a horrific monster of gargantuan heights makes me think this is definitely trying to go back to Godzilla's roots in the most definitive, authentic way possible. Everything else with the setting, the design, the story; it seems this time Godzilla is going to be dark. Way more darker and sinister than he's ever been. I can't wait for December 1st

I think Toho's Godzilla movies are generally just more interesting than what Hollywood is doing with the IP mainly because they're more willing to take chances and do different things with the setting and story. The Monsterverse films really just feel like generic blockbusters with paper thin plots and a lack of any real depth or characterization. That isn't to say that Toho films haven't made the same generic Kaiju films in the past, but they at least seem fairly game to giving a filmmaker the ability to make something a bit more outside the box that's more plot and narrative driven if they want to go that way (The Return of Godzilla, Godzilla vs Biollante, Godzilla vs Megaguris, GMK, Shin Godzilla, the second and third entries of the Gamera trilogy etc.)

Hollywood would probably never sign off on a Shin Godzilla style Goji film or one that was a social/political commentary unless a Chris Nolan/Denis Villeneuve type director with a lot of clout got attached to the project. Every other director would be forced make a soulless/generic blockbuster. For example, Shin Godzilla was nominated and won the equivalent of Best Screenplay at the japanese equivalent to Oscars in 2016/17. I cannot imagine a world where Hollywood produces a Godzilla film with that level of auteurship.

author: @user-fu6bi1jv4g
text: One thing that I noticed in this trailer: Everyone knows that Godzilla is a ‘monster-as-metaphor’ for the nuclear bomb, but it’s not widely known that he was also intended to be a metaphor for the spirits of the fallen soldiers of the Japanese military, who feel that their ultimate sacrifices have been forgotten by the citizens of the Land of the Rising Sun. This is why Godzilla attacks Japan, and not the nation who nuked them at the climax of World War II. In the trailer for this new film, a woman says, “That monster will never forgive us.” This would seem to reflect the ‘monster-as-metaphor-of-the-forgotten-fallen-war-veterans’ approach, in my humble speculation.

author: @robertmiles1603
text: I didn't like the relatively recent movies because they got so far off course from the original idea. Mutating through stages, being 10,000 or whatever feet tall, having a force-field (I.E. as in Planet of the Monsters) and the rest of that. He should just be a giant mutant radioactive firebreathing dinosaur, period, and I'm glad to see that they're finally getting back to basics and returning the character to his roots. No more fucking around. Instead it's Godzilla as he should be, nothing more, nothing less. And I do like the idea of a true classic film about him that doesn't suffer from the qualitative limitations of '50s technology, even if I'm no CGI fan.

author: @JohnSmith-pj6wb
text:
It would be both really cool and historical if in this movie we saw japanese ww2 jet fighters...they we're called nakajima kikka or to americans the "orange blossom"...it was a turbojet flown at the very end of ww2...so technically they could show this being used...

Also...historically the germans sent by uboat nuclear technology to japan in hopes they may make an atomic bomb themselves with uranium and parts to begin..starters kit if you will...this went along with jet tech germans sent in another uboat...historically a few didn't make it but there may have been some that did...so you could say japan built a bomb or something smaller but nuclear and dropped it on godzilla with one of those jet fighters...and the movie would be 99% accurate still ;)

text: Amazing trailer as a fan of the original 1954 movie, i love the shots they managed to catch, and we're probably in for some more call backs. Even though this movie is set before 1954, the sheer terror of Godzilla has always been one of my favorite things about him. I like the monsterverse Godzilla but ive been saying for the longest Godzilla has to go back to his roots, he doesn't always have to help and be the hero. At least i want him to be a feared giant and people running away, its good to have that back and it being set before the original makes it all the better. Can't wait for minus one, and i can't wait for GxK also but minus one has my full attention 🍿🍿🍿. We're eating good!

author: @perrufotrollin1749
text: Parece que sera una obra de arte. Sucede poco después de las bombas por lo que al igual que el godzilla original este representa la maldad y poder del hombre. Lo mas triste es que el japonés dice: Él nunca nos perdonará. Cuando este no es directamente el culpable de las bombas, sino una victima, pero parece ser tan noble que se siente culpable de lo que el hombre ha hecho. Ademas parece que habrá una tercera bomba, lo que muestra como los Americanos no dudaban en usar su armamento nuclear contra objetivos en dicha época sin importarles lo que hacían al no ser suelo americano. Pero me rompe que el japonés se sienta mal a pesar que su gobierno fue el culpable de atacar otros paises. Es solo un civil arrepentido por algo que no hizo. Godzilla una abominación que no debió existir apareciendo en el peor momento de Japón, una tragedia.

author: @makokx7063
text:
A lot of people debating what the line "That monster . . . will never forgive us" is referring to.
In all likelihood this is simply a mistranslation.
The most common meaning of "許す Yurusu" is "to forgive" but unlike in English it also has the meanings of 
To allow, condone, permit, accept, overlook etc.
In many shows and movies when someone is about to be killed they'll say 許してくれ！ "Please forgive me" even if they haven't done anything wrong, which would translate closer to "please permit me to live!" or simply "Spare me!".
When he says その怪物は許しちゃくれない a better translation would be "He's not going to stop until all of us are dead"

author: @louisborselio8608
text: Honestly, I think this movie is going to suck. It doesn't have the natural color tones of real life. It has unnatural CGI tint. Outside of Akira Ifukube, NOBODY  knows how or wants to write Godzilla music. Every other person who writes music for Godzilla movies just wants to show off their artistic ability, and have no concern for what fits a movie. Akira composed stuff for what was seen on screen to capture the perfect feeling. Chances are they're going to use some of Mr. Ifukube's material to try to please the hardcore audience like they did it with Shin Godzilla, but it didn't really help. It just felt tacked on as an afterthought. Plus in a world of CGI overuse, it would have been nice to see some suitmation again.

author: @oldzoot
text: GODZILLA!!! There goes Tokyo. I do love me some Godzilla.

I was sure that it was going to be the sequel to Hideaki Anno's Shin Gojira, this seems to me a carbon copy  of Monsterverse Godzilla. IT seems that TOHO did not give the green light to Hideaki San's sequel. I need to say, not only because I admire his  Evangelion related works, but Shin Gojira was an splendid take on the franchise and it's character. The atmosphere, the urgency and panic, it's the only Godzilla movie that was capable of showing the beauty of destruction, that arguably is the paradigm behind the idea of Godzilla.   movie that I like the most and in my opinion it has no comparison in the franchise, it's as good as it get's o the other sagas. Shin Gojira has everything a great Godzilla movie needs, good actors,  great practical effects and digital effects in fair proportion, great sound and music, a clever, neat, intelligent writing, a genuinely unique monster... The kind of movie that can start serious discussions about very real challenges outside a theater, from the industry itself to the academy, I really mean it. That's it's the magic of cinema. It's sad because Hideaki San came to this world to make that movie. lol I'm getting carried here but Godzilla in the end it's the perfect allegory of the seemingly fictitious, sometimes. however very serious and real threats our planet is enduring right now whichever the causes. A creature that evolves by means of taking advantage of his  inherent  weaknesses to render himself invulnerable, one which at the end in as a last resort before being put down by humans, tries to divide itself into a million gojira.-like humanoids. Very telling. I love that last scene. By no means I'm saying it's a perfect film: perfect things... such illusion has no beauty. But it's final imperfections are hindered as very well managed challenges, It goes beyond the specter, even taking into account it's budget. Pardon my enthusiasm.

author: @BaldPerspective
text:
While I am disappointed Toho will, seemingly, not continue forward with Shin Godzilla, I am excitedly looking forward to this.  I was impressed by the teaser, but this has raised my interest significantly more.  This short trailer shows so many things I've always wanted to see in a live-action Godzilla film, from the full-body reflection shot at 0:24, the people on the collapsing building at 0:33, ppl running like ants from Goji at 0:35, Godzilla walking around in the midst of an atom bomb (!!!) as shown at 0:38, a boat being grabbed by Godzilla's arm from under the ocean's surface at 1:02, a different boat being thrown into the city at 1:06, & Godzilla's immediate landfall at 1:16.  The shot at 0:51 is really similar to some of the shots in Godzilla 2014, & thus not original, but it's great to see it in a Japanese Godzilla film.

The VFX & cinematography are just as good as most of the films Hollywood produces.  The musical score in these two trailers are also excellent, & as a musician I am very much looking forward to hear the score for this.  I am also interested if this will be the beginning of Toho's new MonsterVerse, that they announced back in 2018, or so.  If so, it will be interesting to see how, or even if, this Godzilla (or other Godzillas) will go from personifying tragedy & horror, like Shodai-Goji, to being Japan's hero when he fights other kaiju, specifically more malicious ones like Gigan, King Ghidorah, Hedorah, etc. (Will we see new kaiju??  Will he befriend others like Anguirus, Rodan, & Mothra, like he has in the past?  Will any new kaiju be friend, foe, maybe both?).  If Minus-Goji (not sure if they've officially named him that yet, but they should) does become heroic in later entries, it'll make the line at 1:10 ("That monster will never forgive us.") even more cathartic.

As I mentioned before, I am saddened we won't get more Shin Godzilla, because of all the possibility left behind, but this film is absolutely brimming with possibility, which I definitely can't not be excited for.  Regardless, unlike whatever DC, Marvel, Harry Potter, Star Trek, Star Wars, or anything else does reboot-wise, Godzilla reboots are/have been infinitely more interesting & worthwhile to me.  Go, go Godzilla!

Edit: Lmao, I totally forgot to say, but forget Barbenheimer, the ultimate double feature will be Oppenheimer & this ( *Godzenheimer* ); I legit think this & Oppenheimer will make great companion pieces.

author: @emwa3600
text: Oh boy.  Is Perry Mason in this, too?  I can't wait!  I remain hopeful but this looks far from a good monster film: there is already too much human dialog and too little monster-stomps and tail-clearings.  Toho needs to go back to the 3-round Godzilla film: Minutes 1-30 are Godzilla rising up and destroying a few small coastal areas - yeah, like Yokohama, Yakuska - SMALL areas; of only a few 10-mil people!  Then, G swims away at the end of Minute 30.  In Minute 31, he rises in a new bay, kicks the livin' bejeepers out of that place for 29 minutes, and swims away.  Then, the grand finale starting at Minute 61, he rises over Tokyo, kicks and swipes and breathes hot to the 129-min marks.  And swims away.  All the human dialog is "Scream" and "Oh no".  No "Mommy's", no "Darling I love you's".   Just screams.  The perfect monster movie.

text: Everybody here calling Godzilla "Evil" and "Villain" is missing the point. Godzilla is nature, and it's we who are evil. Death is immoral. It doesn't choose sides. Be humble in the face of nature, but do not fear it.

author: @KorporalNoobs
text:
I think liked the Michael Bay movie when I saw it, but that was just a monster movie with the twist that it was gigantic. Hardly a Godzilla movie.

The resent franchise was cool and all, but it didn't grab me.

I also liked the OGs (with puppets and all) when they came on TV. (surprisingly often during vacation in the Netherlands for some reason)

But these new Japanese ones are actually awesome. The framing in which Godzilla is the center and basically the greater society reacts to him through exemplary character is really cool. And the CGI has the insane scope (quantity a quality in itself etc.) and a dark edge to it, which gives it an unsettling quality.



I will watch it.

text: This is so fucking dope personally I loved how subtle shin Godzilla was at showing that Godzilla was originally a metaphor for the dropping of the atomic bomb and how the government we put in place hurt Japan for more than it helped what makes me so excited about this films concept is the lack of subtly in this trailer of literally showing the version of Godzilla that was developed by and for western consumption destroying Japan as the populace just have to watch in awe. This film isn't a subtle you "guys are missing the point" it is a literal "fuck you guys for making it about you and now we will show you exactly what this symbol means for us and how lightly you have been taking it since its creation".  Its literally the definition of peaceful protest with no naivety, shin was subtle but this is not a subtle film we can turn our eyes from without lying to ourselves as westerners and more importantly as people. Make us squirm Mr. Yamazaki! Make us squirm!

I care so much more about the civilians on the street having to deal with Godzilla, and the Japanese movies kinda get that. Godzilla is a metaphor for the dropping of the atomic bombs on Japan and that shouldn't be all "ra ra military action," it should be horror.

author: @sjp35productions6
text: Thank you Toho Studios!!!! I watched the original Godzilla movie in the early ‘70’s when it was chopped up with scenes of Raymond Burr giving narration as to the action as well as the bad voice over dubbing for the actors. It wasn’t until thirty+ years later when I was able to watch the full movie with subtitles only, which gave me a better sense of what was being conveyed by the actors.  Now, in my sixth decade, I’m as excited about seeing this film as I was when Star Wars came out.  I know I’ll be sad at the end of the movie because of having to wait for the next installment.

author: @hnarjsi2771
text: If Godzilla briefly appeared in Japan in 1947, Japan would have been under the control of the Allied Forces, and the military would have been dismantled and its weapons would have been de-deployed. A Kagero-class destroyer is shown with its main gun removed. There is an obvious scene where Godzilla destroys the bridge of a Takao-class heavy cruiser, suggesting a strong murderous intent and advanced intelligence. The Sokuten-class construction boat has also appeared, but isn't this the first time this warship has been made into a movie?

author: @BrysonRobinson
text:
I've never seen a solo Godzilla film but this looks absolutely insane. I've only seen Godzilla Vs. Kong but that lacks the weight of what Godzilla would actually do to a city/peaople. This has an insane scope while also never shying away from the horrors of what Godzilla causes both physically and mentally. This trailer gave me goosebumps and I'm kind of scared of what the actual film is going to contain at this point, haha.

Japanese cinema is coming to the rescue to save the second half of 2023 and I'm here for it. TOHO has my money, see you guys at the cinema.

author: @tier45acp
text:
I noticed upon re-watching and slowing the trailer down that the nuclear looking explosion in the ocean was actually his thermo-nuclear breath going through a battle ship!. Which makes me speculate the nuke going off in the city which I assumed would have been Nagasaki or Hiroshima, is instead what happens when he uses his attack and perhaps it damages him as well hence the scarring as he roars at the end. That would be the only logical way of tempering how often he can use such a devastating thing plot wise. 
Also we don't know how they will handle the actual atomic bomb droppings story wise. It being him using his breath would be interesting spin on it.

author: @yueshijoorya601
text:
Fun fact, when the first atom bomb went off, the huge EMP knocked out all communications. The rest of the country did not know what happened, authorities only received myriad reports about a loud boom and Hiroshima being uncontactable, and that something terrible has happened there.

The first few seconds of this trailer captures that. I can believe that a superstitious few thought that an actual kaiju surfaced.

author: @afrinaut3094
text: The original Godzilla was meant to be a metaphor for the cruelty of atomic weaponry. It wasn’t until later, that Japan pivoted Godzilla, to representing the uncontrollable forces of nature, and sort of a justice through nature and balance metaphor (which might be related to true Shinto). The ladder is my favorite. But I’m also open to the original metaphor as well. With that said, unlike Oppenheimer, I’m hoping this movie at least acknowledges a little bit…. The Japan was a fascist-state in World War II.

author: @cmillspa1
text: I love Shin Godzilla to death, but it will be nice to see a return of the pissed off Godzilla who purposefully wants to obliterate everything in his path instead of doing so unintentionally. It’s like a sentient natural disaster that’s out for human blood. Brutal stuff. Back when 2014 Legendary Godzilla was coming out, I thought that’s the road that Hollywood was going to take, but they chose to make Godzilla more of a semi-benevolent force of good, or at least “balance”. Legendary monsters are good, but I’ve always liked the idea of Godzilla best when he’s punishing humanity for his very existence.

author: @FMAChet
text:
"I fear all we have done is to awaken a sleeping giant and fill him with a terrible resolve" - Vermont Royster. Such words may have meaning in this film. As well the following quotation.

"That monster will never forgive us" Such a foreboding line in a what may very well be one of the darkest films in the Godzilla franchise.

Never have I seen a trailer like this since Shin Godzilla's 1st trailer, with the haunting "Persecution of the Masses" playing.This trailer heavily emphasizes a scared and wounded Japan, healing from the wounds of WWII, about to face a crisis that will invoke despair.

It's very understandable that the very fear of paranoia of the Atomic bomb takes form of a destructive and very vengeful leviathan of death, which in reality is a allegory of said fear, a god theorized in mythology and legend now a very real nightmare, looks scared and wounded, but with a resolve undeterred and unmeasured anger and hatred.

From what has been shown so far, it looks that because of the war, and apparently the fire bombings of Tokyo, has not only awaken, but inadvertently wounded this deity from it's slumber, invoking it's wrath before a war scarred land and it's people the scars it now carries. Rising from the earth, much like Mothra Vs Godzilla in 1962, this god or devil of vengeance plans to leave unrivaled destruction and endless death in it's wake.

I look forward to see how this film goes.

author: @wymg4480
text: This movie gonna be epic. Always loved the OG Godzilla as a walking herald of destruction. However, that being said, ppl shit on the monsterverse movies too much. Just cuz Godzilla isnt what he used to be, doesnt make them bad. And these complaints keep saying that Godzilla is "too good" but he isnt even a hero. Hes a King thats protecting his territory and establishing dominance. Hes not a protector of humanity. Hes more than willing to wipe them out if they overstep their boundaries like with mechagodzilla. In all honestly, him being a million year old ancient alpha predator was more probable than some marine species turned by radiation into a monster within a few years time. But regardless, cant we all just enjoy both sides of him? Just accept that there are different forms of Godzillas. Liking the OG is not a problem. But you dont gotta say the monsterverse movies are shit because of that.

author: @AnthonyMcqueen1987
text:
Okay not bad still keeping Godzilla a mystery Toho showing him doing what we expect him to do. But I refuse to judge this till the film comes out because we have seen this before with Ultima and Shin and those turned out to be a waste of time.

So I hope Toho is listening to the fans and bringing us something he have not seen before. I am interested in what he can do rather than cosmetic changes.

Not going to jump for joy like everyone else here.

If this is before the 1954 film then Godzilla is not the king of the monsters. He needs to fight Anguirus in or for that to happen which he does in 1955.

In my 30 years of being a fan Toho is a mixed bag going back and fourth between timelines.

author: @theadorabletk
text: That roar. That freaking roar. There's something really unsettling about this G's roar. It's the agonized scream of something in unfathomable pain lashing out at whatever it can reach. I find it really fascinating that this film seems to take place during post-war Japan. The original Gojira was filmed during that time, so this is definitely a return to roots. Curious to see what kind of themes the movie's going to have, especially since this could take place post-war. Not only will Japan be dealing with the aftermath of literal atomic bombs, they're going to have to go up against a creature that quite literally embodies the fallout of nuclear war.

author: @kaijuar2003
text:
"That monster....will never forgive us."
I don't know about anyone else, but since the character says that, I THINK this Godzilla KNOWS why he's attacking people and why he's so violent, he has an ACTUAL reason to be this violent towards humanity. He ISN'T like the other incarnations, not like the original Gojira, this Godzilla legitimately has a REAL reason to be this hostile.

And another thing, I also THINK that at the end of the movie, Godzilla WILL find a way to forgive humanity since the character mentions forgiveness.


I'm MOST LIKELY wrong about the forgiveness part, but that one specific line in the trailer REALLY gets me thinking about this particular Godzilla. By the way, just recently on Twitter, I came across a tweet that used Godzilla as a way to convey that nuclear power plants are the safest and best way to gain energy, which Godzilla ISN'T about energy/electricity but nuclear weapons and the destruction they have on humanity and the pkanet as a whole, so yeah, the Twotter users DIDN'T know shit about the message Godzilla is MEANT to convey.

author: @danielramsey6141
text:
Godzilla will always be A national Symbol for Japan, the Coin-Duality of his existence is just so perfect when you realized that when he was made, Japan was in a state of mourning.

And during the 60s & early 70s, Japan finally was able to change, to forget about war and  it’s horrors, changing Godzilla into a kinder creature even though his birth was from a horrid moment in human history.

The United States, are not willing to villainize themselves, the A and H Bombs are what made Godzilla.  Godzilla is seen as Hubris.  But he’s never seen that way to America, and that’s very sad, it’s disgusting when you realize it in great context and the comparisons between the two Nations.

It’s a damn shame that the 2014 Godzilla film never came close to making Godzilla represent that Darker, personal half.  

Yet, we also try to pass off “Oppenheimer” as being the equivalent to what Tragedy Godzilla inspires.

author: @GodIsInTheTv
text:
Ive been taking animation classes. 
And the teacher told me the #1 thing that is neglected when doing realistic animation, is how the skeleton would look and move under the creatures skin.
We would do things like, study the way animals move, and compare that to how their skeletons move with the skin & muscle removed.
That being said..now all i see is inaccuracies in models. The way Godzillas jaw opens, does not make sense.. But yea.. its just a movie so okay ill move on i guess..

author: @TheJuRK
text:
As much as I love the special effects of the modern Godzilla in the American movies, those movies are the dumbest stories I've ever seen.  
I went to see Shin Godzilla and was fascinated by how the Japanese treated their greatest monster in a new film, showing serious government and military responses to that particular major emergency.
But Godzilla Minus One looks like it might actually be THE ONE we've all been waiting for: a dark, solid horror story with great special effects that finally hits the bullseye.  
I'm really looking forward to this!

author: @FlawedCoil82
text: I don’t like Godzilla being the enemy because that inevitably means he MUST be defeated/killed by the humans, whom I am never rooting for. I want a Godzilla that I can love; not one that I am totally repulsed by. “Shin Godzilla” was such an overpowered, ugly-ass lumbering volcano that moved super slow and made him ungodly boring (don’t even get me started on that god-awful anime trilogy…virtually the only “Godzilla” I hate more than Tristar’s Zilla). I want to see Godzilla fighting against other monsters. I was always struck by his courage to fight the ugliest, larger, most evil looking monsters that Toho could send his way. That made him endearing. I do at least like this design the best of all the Reiwa era designs but I have hated pretty much everything Toho has put out with “Godzilla”s name attached since “Shin Godzilla”. Honestly, the definitive Godzilla I loved the most tragically died in 1995. Nothing else Toho, Tristar nor Legendary has offered has come close to that undisputed king of the monsters since.

author: @princessmaly
text:
"That monster will never forgive us."

Nope. Never. Literally four movies ago:
"If your high praise is all we have, let us not be without you."

As long as we continue waging wars over nothing, polluting in every conceivable way, denying or forgetting our atrocities, as long as people care more about power than doing the right thing, as long as a single nuclear weapon remains on this planet, Godzilla is never, ever going away. And there's nothing hollywood or anyone else can do about that.

Maybe some day humans might live to see a time when we don't need Godzilla anymore. But that sure as hell isn't now. 1947 or 2023, doesn't matter, it's all the same anwyas. Post-war extends forever.

author: @TheBlackKS1
text:
While I am looking forward to seeing this at some point and the trailer looks great, I do wish that they kept the fact that it was a Godzilla movie a secret in some way. They could just say it's a new movie from Toho called Minus One, show the destruction, devastation, and the people moments with no images of Godzilla, getting people interested in what is causing the destruction, why an explosion was going off, or what the monster could be, then reveal it in the theater itself.

I get it though, Godzilla is a brand name that will sell and would likely not get as many viewings on initial release if they did that but imagine the shock when you go to a movie with some mystery about it, not realizing it was really going to be a Godzilla movie. Think of it like the first Godzilla movie, where you don't actually see Godzilla until about 20 minutes in and even then, it's only a head shot.

author: @Peaceful_Gojira
text:
I'm very glad to see a bona fide re-make of Gojira (1954), and one that is finally gonna have the modern technology and cinematic methods to actually show HOW TRULY devistating Godzilla is not just as a monster, but a force of bastardized-human nature.

One thing I am sad about though is that Toho hasn't released a sequel to Shin Godzilla, and that movie came out awhile ago now...I hope that's still in the cards for Toho, because that put Japanese Godzilla back ok the map for me (like many, I'm sure).

Be safe everyone. Excited to start off the Christmas season right, haha.

author: @foomp
text:
I'm ALWAYS for Godzilla films. I'm just hoping they don't pull a 2014 move and barely ever show it. I liked that movie, but holy shit was it a sorely missed opportunity with all the stupid sneak peak type of shots of Godzilla. Shin Godzilla has, thus far, been the creme of the crop with these films. So much potential lore and a look into how terrifyingly unstable Godzilla actually is.

It'll be hard for another film to top that one or even come close to how impressive they made Godzilla. I'm all for an even darker tone for the movie though, as even with Shin, some of the standout scenes involved people dying in rather tragic ways.

author: @RikuDarkness500
text:
Einstein TURNS to leave. Up the hill, Strauss approaches... 

OPPENHEIMER
Albert? When i came to you with those calculations?

Einstein pauses. I watch raindrops make circles on the surface of the pond. 

OPPENHEIMER (CONT'D) 
We were worried that we'd start a chain reaction that would destroy the entire world... 

EINSTEIN
I remember it well. What of it? 

OPPENHEIMER
I believe we did. 

Einstein PALES. TURNS, passing Strauss without a word. The sound of FEET STAMPING... 

CLOSE IN ON: my staring eyes as i visualize THE EXPANDING NUCLEAR ARSENALS OF THE WORLD... THE FEET, FASTER AND FASTER- 

When i can take it no longer, i JAM my eyes CLOSES and we-

CUT TO BLACK. 

CREDITS. 

END.

- Oppenheimer (2023)
Screenplay by Christopher Nolan.

text:
Monsters are tragic beings. They’re not bad [willingly]. They’re born too tall, too strong, too heavy; that’s their tragedy. They don’t attack [mankind] voluntarily, but because of their physical dimensions they cause danger and grief; therefore man defends himself against them. After several stories of this type, the public finds sympathy for the monsters.
Ishiro Honda.

author: @hyperyami396
text: I'm not super pumped for this movie mainly because at this point I just want to see Toho's Godzilla interact with some of the iconic monsters from his universe and others if possible with amazing practical, CGI, VFX effects. I want to see the creators adapt King Caesar, Anguirus, Mothra, Gigan, Destoroyah, Rodan, Mechagodzilla, King Ghidorah, Jet Jaguar, Mechani-Kong, Mecha-King Ghidorah, Space Godzilla and the list just goes on and on, yet we get another one of these deep Godzilla movie showing the destruction... fine, but after this movie they need to give it a break and take a chance on some new material. Everybody already knows what Godzilla represents and his origin story. It would be incredible if Godzilla faced off against some new Kaiju Monsters as well as old ones. I'm sure Toho will make an amazing film with this project, but I just think it's time for Godzilla to fight some else other than humanity 24/7.

author: @gallifrey1212
text: This looks amazing! Toho is really going back to Godzilla's roots and portraying him as the destructive force of nature that he is. I don't "see" Godzilla as ever being just "good" or "evil." He is essentially an allegory for the consequences of mankind's obsession with violence and destruction. I mean, yeah, the U.S. got the whole nuclear armaments thing started, but many countries have nukes now. By possessing such things and creating even more destrucitve weapons, humanity may very well have lost sight of the horrible consequences their actions can cause. Godzilla is like a long-lasting and enduring (fictional) physical reminder that some choices will loom over humanity for many, many years to come: "You did that, and now you have to live with it." ("it" being Godzilla in this case)

text:
Here it is at long last! The brand new trailer for "Godzilla Minus One" and it looks both epic and amazing in every sense of the word!

It’s still very light on story content but gives us enough new footage to get fans hyped for the film!Just look at the sheer terror and spectacle this trailer generated! Godzilla looks so raw and primal it’s amazing and seeing those battleships get obliterated by him is a sight to behold! This movie is going to rock so hard! Once again move over Hollywood the real Godzilla is back and is ready to be unleashed upon the world! Welcome back Godzilla! 😍❤️

Also seeing the MPA Rating System at the beginning of the official English subtitle trailer is just amazing! They are treating the film as a wide regular release and not like a limited time Fathom Events! I’d love to see this trailer in my theaters sometime, that would be a huge surprise!

author: @nerdsman567
text:
This gives me very similar vibes to the 2012 Comic-Con trailer for “Godzilla 2014” (Before Legendary Pictures pulled the “Bait and Switch” on everyone). The actual movie we got with G2014 was the absolute BARE MINIMUM of what you could even CALL a Godzilla movie! It seems like this movie will have actual substance to it and actually depict a apocalyptic take on Godzilla, much like what Legendary initially promised with that 2012 trailer, but abandoned it and went for a much more watered down take with G2014 and the rest of the MonsterVerse, which have gradually become overly campy and cartoonish.

Here’s hoping “Minus One” succeeds where G2014 failed in its attempt at making a grounded and serious Godzilla movie (Dull storyline, bland and forgettable human characters, constantly cutting away from the monsters, shrouding the monsters in constant darkness, etc.). Judging from this trailer, it looks like we’ll actually get to see the destruction Godzilla causes, unlike G2014, which constantly cut away to the aftermath. Obviously, it’s too early to judge “Minus One” properly, however, as far as tone and atmosphere goes, THIS movie is what G2014 should have been!
